{{BatBox (/c)}}

	Changes console's color locally (instead of {../color|COLOR} that sets
	console color globaly}. IE. the color is aplied only to the text that will
	be printed after the command execution.

{{Synopsis}}

${	BATBOX /c code_colour}

	Changes console's color locally.

	- {code_colour} : A code that specify the colors to be set. Usualy,
	this code is specified on {hexadecimal}. Is this case, {code_colour}'s
	form is {0xYX}, where :
	
		-- {X} is the background colour.
		
		-- {Y} is the foreground colour (text colour).
	
	{X} and {Y} must be values among these values :
		
			- 0 : Black 

			- 1 : Dark blue
			
			- 2 : Green
			
			- 3 : Grey-Blue
			
			- 4 : Marroon

            - 5 : Dark red			
			
			- 6 : Kaki
			
			- 7 : Bright grey 
			
			- 8 : Grey
			
			- 9 : Bright blue
			   
			- A : Bright green
			   
			- B : Cyan
			     
			- C : Red
			 
			- D : Pink
			       
			- E : Yellow
			
			- F : White
			
{{Notes}}

	When specified in {hexadecimal}, colour codes are identical to colour
	codes of the command {../color|COLOR}, except that it requires to be preceded
	by {0x}

	If you specify same colours for both background and foreground, then the text output
	will be hidden as text and background color are the same.
	
